                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           State medical aid to Kalpana
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                               
	Bhubaneswar, June 19: The state government today arranged for the treatment of ace mountaineer Kalpana Dash at Kalinga Hospital, a multi-speciality health centre in the city, a day after Nationalist Congress Party announced that it would bear all expenses for her treatment.         
	Kalpana had scaled the Everest on May 21. She fell ill at the base camp on May 25 and was admitted to a Kathmandu hospital. She was brought home early this month. Chief secretary Ajit Kumar Tripathy today told reporters that the government had decided to admit Kalpana to the Kalinga Hospital since her health was in bad shape. The state is going to bear all the expenses of her treatment. Earlier, sources had said that Kalpana would be shifted to All India Institute of Medical Sciences in New Delhi.         
	Chief minister Naveen Patnaik has also announced a cash prize of Rs 5 lakh for the ace mountaineer for making Orissa proud.         
	Kalpana, who met the chief secretary at the secretariat in the morning, expressed her gratitude for the support and co-operation provided to her by the government. The chief secretary had also helped her to mobilise funds before her expedition. Kalpana expressed her gratitude to the NCP leaders, as well, when they met her at her Dhenkanal residence.                                                                                                                                                                         
